00:12:16.330 --> 00:12:17.100
have gone round

270
00:12:17.100 --> 00:12:18.270
And none of them beenworn;

271
00:12:18.270 --> 00:12:19.600
and, for a name,

272
00:12:19.600 --> 00:12:21.330
Now puts the drowsy andneglected act

273
00:12:21.330 --> 00:12:24.970
Freshly on me: 'tis surelyfor a name.

274
00:12:24.970 --> 00:12:27.070
I warrant it is:

275
00:12:27.070 --> 00:12:29.400
and thy head stands sotickle on thy shoulders

276
00:12:29.400 --> 00:12:31.230
that a milkmaid, if she bein love,

277
00:12:31.230 --> 00:12:34.300
may sigh it off.

278
00:12:36.100 --> 00:12:40.570
(crying)

279
00:12:47.600 --> 00:12:52.200
Send after the duke andappeal to him.

280
00:12:52.200 --> 00:12:54.730
I have done so, but he'snot to be found.

281
00:12:54.730 --> 00:12:57.170
I prithee, Lucio, do methis kind service:

282
00:12:57.170 --> 00:12:59.270
This day my sister shouldthe cloister enter

283
00:12:59.270 --> 00:13:01.070
And there receive herapprobation:

284
00:13:01.070 --> 00:13:03.470
Acquaint her with thedanger of my state:

285
00:13:03.470 --> 00:13:04.670
Implore her, in my voice,

286
00:13:04.670 --> 00:13:07.370
that she make friends tothe strict deputy;

287
00:13:07.370 --> 00:13:09.070
bid herself assay him:

288
00:13:09.070 --> 00:13:11.400
I have great hope in that;for in her youth

289
00:13:11.400 --> 00:13:13.570
There is a prone andspeechless dialect,

290
00:13:13.570 --> 00:13:14.800
Such as move men;

291
00:13:14.800 --> 00:13:16.430
beside, she hathprosperous art

292
00:13:16.430 --> 00:13:17.930
When she will play withreason and discourse,

293
00:13:17.930 --> 00:13:19.700
And well she can persuade.

294
00:13:19.700 --> 00:13:20.630
I pray she may;

295
00:13:20.630 --> 00:13:22.430
as well for theencouragement of the like,

296
00:13:22.430 --> 00:13:25.100
which else would standunder grievous imposition,

297
00:13:25.100 --> 00:13:27.100
as for the enjoying of thylife,

298
00:13:27.100 --> 00:13:28.830
who I would be sorryshould be thus

299
00:13:28.830 --> 00:13:33.570
foolishly lost at a gameof tick-tack. I'll to her.

300
00:13:33.570 --> 00:13:38.630
I thank you, good friendLucio.

301
00:13:44.930 --> 00:13:47.100
No, holy father; throwaway that thought;

302
00:13:47.100 --> 00:13:49.330
Believe not that thedribbling dart of love

303
00:13:49.330 --> 00:13:51.400
Can pierce a completebosom.

304
00:13:51.400 --> 00:13:52.530
Why I desire thee

305
00:13:52.530 --> 00:13:53.600
To give me secret harbour,

306
00:13:53.600 --> 00:13:55.530
hath a purpose more graveand wrinkled

307
00:13:55.530 --> 00:13:58.100
than the aims and ends ofburning youth.

308
00:13:58.100 --> 00:14:00.100
May your grace speak ofit?

309
00:14:00.100 --> 00:14:02.370
My holy sir, none betterknows than you

310
00:14:02.370 --> 00:14:04.800
How I have ever loved thelife removed

311
00:14:04.800 --> 00:14:06.770
And held in idle price tohaunt assemblies

312
00:14:06.770 --> 00:14:10.930
Where youth, and cost, andwitless bravery keeps.

313
00:14:10.930 --> 00:14:13.530
I have deliver'd to LordAngelo,

314
00:14:13.530 --> 00:14:16.130
A man of stricture andfirm abstinence,

315
00:14:16.130 --> 00:14:19.000
My absolute power andplace here in Vienna,

316
00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:22.100
And he supposes metravell'd to Poland;

317
00:14:22.100 --> 00:14:23.670
For so I have strew'd itin the common ear,

318
00:14:23.670 --> 00:14:26.730
And so it is received.Now, pious sir,

319
00:14:26.730 --> 00:14:28.730
You will demand of me whyI do this?

320
00:14:28.730 --> 00:14:30.600
Gladly, my lord.

321
00:14:30.600 --> 00:14:35.130
We have strict statutesand most biting laws.

322
00:14:35.130 --> 00:14:38.170
The needful bits and curbsto headstrong weeds,

323
00:14:38.170 --> 00:14:41.800
Which for this fourteenyears we have let slip;

324
00:14:41.800 --> 00:14:43.800
Even like an o'ergrownlion in a cave,

325
00:14:43.800 --> 00:14:46.800
That goes not out to prey.

326
00:14:46.800 --> 00:14:48.000
Now, as fond fathers,

327
00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:50.500
Having bound up thethreatening twigs of birch,

328
00:14:50.500 --> 00:14:52.230
Only to stick it in theirchildren's sight

329
00:14:52.230 --> 00:14:55.170
For terror, not to use,

330
00:14:55.170 --> 00:14:58.000
in time the rod becomesmore mock'd

331
00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:00.070
than fear'd; so ourdecrees,

332
00:15:00.070 --> 00:15:03.370
Dead to infliction, tothemselves are dead;

333
00:15:03.370 --> 00:15:06.200
And liberty plucks justiceby the nose;

334
00:15:06.200 --> 00:15:07.570
The baby beats the nurse,

335
00:15:07.570 --> 00:15:10.800
and quite athwart goes alldecorum.

336
00:15:17.230 --> 00:15:18.730
It rested in your grace

337
00:15:18.730 --> 00:15:21.730
To unloose this tied-upjustice when you pleased:

338
00:15:21.730 --> 00:15:23.170
And it in you moredreadful

339
00:15:23.170 --> 00:15:25.000
would have seem'd than inLord Angelo.

340
00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:26.430
I do fear, too dreadful:

341
00:15:26.430 --> 00:15:29.630
Sith 'twas my fault togive the people scope,

342
00:15:29.630 --> 00:15:31.370
'Twould be my tyranny tostrike and gall them

343
00:15:31.370 --> 00:15:32.600
For what I bid them do:

344
00:15:32.600 --> 00:15:34.400
for we bid this be done,

345
00:15:34.400 --> 00:15:36.270
When evil deeds have theirpermissive pass

346
00:15:36.270 --> 00:15:38.300
And not the punishment.

347
00:15:38.300 --> 00:15:40.100
Therefore indeed, myfather,

348
00:15:40.100 --> 00:15:42.470
I have on Angelo imposedthe office;

349
00:15:42.470 --> 00:15:46.630
Who may, in the ambush ofmy name, strike home,

350
00:15:46.630 --> 00:15:49.600
But my nature never inthe fight

351
00:15:49.600 --> 00:15:51.830
To do in slander.

352
00:15:51.830 --> 00:15:54.300
And to behold his sway,

353
00:15:54.300 --> 00:15:56.100
I will, as 'twere abrother of your order,

354
00:15:56.100 --> 00:15:59.730
Visit both prince andpeople:

355
00:15:59.730 --> 00:16:00.670
therefore, I prithee,

356
00:16:00.670 --> 00:16:02.630
Supply me with the habitand instruct me

357
00:16:02.630 --> 00:16:04.130
How I may formally inperson

358
00:16:04.130 --> 00:16:06.600
bear me like a true friar.

359
00:16:06.600 --> 00:16:08.100
More reasons for thisaction

360
00:16:08.100 --> 00:16:10.500
At our more leisure shallI render you;

361
00:16:10.500 --> 00:16:16.430
Only, this one: LordAngelo is precise;

362
00:16:16.430 --> 00:16:18.030
Stands at a guard withenvy;

363
00:16:18.030 --> 00:16:20.130
scarce confesses that hisblood flows,

364
00:16:20.130 --> 00:16:23.200
or that his appetite ismore to bread than stone:

365
00:16:23.200 --> 00:16:24.170
hence shall we see,

366
00:16:24.170 --> 00:16:27.300
If power change purpose,what our seemers be.

367
00:16:29.030 --> 00:16:32.300
And have you nuns nofarther privileges?

368
00:16:32.300 --> 00:16:34.330
Are not these largeenough?

369
00:16:34.330 --> 00:16:37.600
Yes, truly; I speak not asdesiring more;

370
00:16:37.600 --> 00:16:39.470
But rather wishing a morestrict restraint

371
00:16:39.470 --> 00:16:43.230
Upon the sisterhood, thevotarists of Saint Clare.

372
00:16:43.230 --> 00:16:45.630
Ho! Peace be in thisplace!

373
00:16:45.630 --> 00:16:47.000
Who's that which calls?

374
00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:48.900
It is a man's voice.

375
00:16:48.900 --> 00:16:51.100
Gentle Isabella, turn youthe key,

376
00:16:51.100 --> 00:16:53.300
and know his business ofhim;

377
00:16:53.300 --> 00:16:57.770
You may, I may not; youare yet not sworn.

378
00:16:57.770 --> 00:17:00.730
When you have vow'd, youmust not speak with men

379
00:17:00.730 --> 00:17:03.030
But in the presence of theprioress:

380
00:17:03.030 --> 00:17:05.630
Then, if you speak, youmust not show your face,

381
00:17:05.630 --> 00:17:09.430
Or, if you show your face,you must not speak.

382
00:17:09.430 --> 00:17:11.000
Hello! (off camera)

383
00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:13.570
He calls again; I prayyou, answer him.

384
00:17:23.900 --> 00:17:26.870
Peace and prosperity! Whois't that calls

385
00:17:26.870 --> 00:17:29.830
Hail, virgin, if you be,

386
00:17:29.830 --> 00:17:32.800
as those cheek-rosesproclaim you are no less!

387
00:17:32.800 --> 00:17:33.670
Can you so stead me

388
00:17:33.670 --> 00:17:36.200
as bring me to the sightof Isabella,

389
00:17:36.200 --> 00:17:38.070
A novice of this place andthe fair sister

390
00:17:38.070 --> 00:17:41.200
To her unhappy brotherClaudio?

391
00:17:41.200 --> 00:17:44.630
Why 'her unhappy brother'?let me ask,

392
00:17:44.630 --> 00:17:46.630
The rather for I now mustmake you know

393
00:17:46.630 --> 00:17:49.100
I am that Isabella and hissister.

394
00:17:49.100 --> 00:17:52.330
Gentle and fair, yourbrother kindly greets you:

395
00:17:52.330 --> 00:17:56.030
Not to be weary with you,he's in prison.

396
00:17:58.730 --> 00:18:01.000
Woe me! for what?

397
00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:03.470
For that which, if myselfmight be his judge,

398
00:18:03.470 --> 00:18:06.200
He should receive hispunishment in thanks:

399
00:18:06.200 --> 00:18:08.730
He hath got his friendwith child.

400
00:18:08.730 --> 00:18:10.800
Sir, make me not yourstory.

401
00:18:10.800 --> 00:18:12.730
It is true.

402
00:18:12.730 --> 00:18:15.470
I would not--though 'tismy familiar sin

403
00:18:15.470 --> 00:18:17.600
With maids to seem thelapwing and to jest,

404
00:18:17.600 --> 00:18:21.630
Tongue far from heart--playwith all virgins so:

405
00:18:21.630 --> 00:18:23.570
I hold you as a thingensky'd and sainted.

406
00:18:23.570 --> 00:18:26.530
By your renouncement animmortal spirit,

407
00:18:26.530 --> 00:18:27.600
And to be talk'd with insincerity,

408
00:18:27.600 --> 00:18:28.530
As with a saint.

409
00:18:28.530 --> 00:18:32.430
You do blaspheme the goodin mocking me.

410
00:18:32.430 --> 00:18:36.630
Do not believe it. Fewnessand truth, 'tis thus:

411
00:18:36.630 --> 00:18:44.330
Your brother and his loverhave embraced:

412
00:18:44.330 --> 00:18:46.230
As those that feed growfull,

413
00:18:46.230 --> 00:18:48.130
as blossoming time thatfrom the seedness

414
00:18:48.130 --> 00:18:50.770
the bare fallow brings toteeming foison,

415
00:18:50.770 --> 00:18:52.430
even so her plenteous womb

416
00:18:52.430 --> 00:18:56.130
Expresseth his full tilthand husbandry.

417
00:18:56.130 --> 00:18:59.530
Some one with child byhim? My cousin Juliet?

418
00:18:59.530 --> 00:19:00.870
Is she your cousin?

419
00:19:00.870 --> 00:19:03.000
Adoptedly; as school-maidschange their names

420
00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:04.930
By vain though aptaffection.

421
00:19:04.930 --> 00:19:05.870
She it is.

422
00:19:05.870 --> 00:19:07.870
O, let him marry her.

423
00:19:07.870 --> 00:19:09.330
This is the point.

424
00:19:09.330 --> 00:19:12.400
The duke is very strangelygone from hence;

425
00:19:12.400 --> 00:19:14.700
Bore many gentlemen,myself being one,

426
00:19:14.700 --> 00:19:16.370
In hand and hope ofaction:

427
00:19:16.370 --> 00:19:17.430
but we do learn

428
00:19:17.430 --> 00:19:19.430
By those that know thevery nerves of state,

429
00:19:19.430 --> 00:19:21.800
His givings-out were of aninfinite distance

430
00:19:21.800 --> 00:19:23.900
From his true-meantdesign.

431
00:19:23.900 --> 00:19:24.900
Upon his place,

432
00:19:24.900 --> 00:19:26.600
And with full line of hisauthority,

433
00:19:26.600 --> 00:19:28.830
Governs Lord Angelo;

434
00:19:28.830 --> 00:19:32.800
a man whose blood is verysnow-broth;

435
00:19:32.800 --> 00:19:33.800
one who never feels

436
00:19:33.800 --> 00:19:36.570
The wanton stings andmotions of the sense,

437
00:19:36.570 --> 00:19:39.070
But doth rebate and blunthis natural edge

438
00:19:39.070 --> 00:19:42.630
With profits of the mind,study and fast.

439
00:19:42.630 --> 00:19:45.870
He--to give fear to useand liberty,

440
00:19:45.870 --> 00:19:48.000
Which have for long run bythe hideous law,

441
00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:51.330
As mice by lions--hathpick'd out an act,

442
00:19:51.330 --> 00:19:53.530
Under whose heavy senseyour brother's life

443
00:19:53.530 --> 00:19:55.170
Falls into forfeit:

444
00:19:55.170 --> 00:19:57.000
he arrests him on it;

445
00:19:57.000 --> 00:19:58.870
And follows close therigour of the statute,

446
00:19:58.870 --> 00:20:00.870
To make him an example.

447
00:20:00.870 --> 00:20:02.630
All hope is gone,

448
00:20:02.630 --> 00:20:05.530
Unless you have the graceby your fair prayer

449
00:20:05.530 --> 00:20:08.970
To soften Angelo:

450
00:20:08.970 --> 00:20:10.900
and that's my pith ofbusiness

451
00:20:10.900 --> 00:20:15.300
'Twixt you and your poorbrother.

452
00:20:15.300 --> 00:20:18.770
Doth he so seek his life?

453
00:20:18.770 --> 00:20:20.630
Has censured him already;

454
00:20:20.630 --> 00:20:24.200
and, as I hear, the provost hatha warrant for his execution.

455
00:20:25.370 --> 00:20:27.030
Alas! what poor ability'sin me

456
00:20:27.030 --> 00:20:29.130
To do him good?

457
00:20:29.130 --> 00:20:30.900
Assay the power you have.

458
00:20:30.900 --> 00:20:33.470
My power? Alas, I doubt--

459
00:20:33.470 --> 00:20:35.300
Our doubts are traitors

460
00:20:35.300 --> 00:20:37.670
And make us lose the goodwe oft might win

461
00:20:37.670 --> 00:20:40.730
By fearing to attempt.

462
00:20:40.730 --> 00:20:41.970
Go to Lord Angelo,

463
00:20:41.970 --> 00:20:44.730
And let him learn to know,when maidens sue,

464
00:20:44.730 --> 00:20:48.470
Men give like gods; butwhen they weep and kneel,

465
00:20:48.470 --> 00:20:50.700
All their petitions are asfreely theirs

466
00:20:50.700 --> 00:20:54.070
As they themselves wouldowe them.

467
00:20:54.070 --> 00:20:56.730
I'll see what I can do.

468
00:20:56.730 --> 00:20:58.100
But speedily.

469
00:20:58.100 --> 00:20:59.500
I will about it straight;

470
00:20:59.500 --> 00:21:01.170
No longer staying but togive the mother

471
00:21:01.170 --> 00:21:04.330
Notice of my affair. Ihumbly thank you:

472
00:21:04.330 --> 00:21:09.930
Commend me to my brother:

473
00:21:09.930 --> 00:21:12.800
soon at night I'll send himcertain word of my success.

474
00:21:12.800 --> 00:21:14.500
I humbly take my leave.

475
00:21:14.500 --> 00:21:16.330
Good sir, adieu.

476
00:21:18.600 --> 00:21:21.700
We must not make ascarecrow of the law,

477
00:21:21.700 --> 00:21:24.100
Setting it up to fear thebirds of prey,

478
00:21:24.100 --> 00:21:25.570
And let it keep one shape,

479
00:21:25.570 --> 00:21:27.170
till custom make it theirperch

480
00:21:27.170 --> 00:21:28.570
and not their terror.

481
00:21:28.570 --> 00:21:29.670
Ay, but yet let us bekeen,

482
00:21:29.670 --> 00:21:31.900
and rather cut a little,

483
00:21:31.900 --> 00:21:34.630
Than fall, and bruise todeath.

484
00:21:34.630 --> 00:21:36.600
Alas, this gentleman

485
00:21:36.600 --> 00:21:40.130
Whom I would save, had amost noble father!

486
00:21:41.230 --> 00:21:42.400
Let but your honour know,

487
00:21:42.400 --> 00:21:45.130
Whom I believe to be moststrait in virtue,

488
00:21:45.130 --> 00:21:47.430
That, in the working ofyour own affections,

489
00:21:47.430 --> 00:21:51.570
Had time cohered with placeor place with wishing,

490
00:21:51.570 --> 00:21:52.970
Or that the resoluteacting of your blood

491
00:21:52.970 --> 00:21:56.100
Could have attain'd theeffect of your own purpose,

492
00:21:56.100 --> 00:21:58.570
Whether you had notsometime in your life

493
00:21:58.570 --> 00:22:03.630
Err'd in this point whichnow you censure him,

494
00:22:03.630 --> 00:22:07.100
And pull'd the law uponyou.

495
00:22:07.100 --> 00:22:10.000
'Tis one thing to betempted, Escalus,

496
00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:14.270
Another thing to fall.

497
00:22:14.270 --> 00:22:15.800
I not deny,

498
00:22:15.800 --> 00:22:18.830
The jury, passing on theprisoner's life,

499
00:22:18.830 --> 00:22:20.230
May in the sworn twelve

500
00:22:20.230 --> 00:22:22.670
have a thief or twoguiltier than him they try.

501
00:22:22.670 --> 00:22:25.600
What's open made to justice,that justice seizes:

502
00:22:25.600 --> 00:22:26.470
what know the laws

503
00:22:26.470 --> 00:22:29.300
That thieves do pass onthieves?

504
00:22:29.300 --> 00:22:30.700
'Tis very pregnant,

505
00:22:30.700 --> 00:22:31.900
The jewel that we find,

506
00:22:31.900 --> 00:22:33.770
we stoop and take'tbecause we see it;

507
00:22:33.770 --> 00:22:35.170
but what we do not see wetread upon,

508
00:22:35.170 --> 00:22:37.400
and never think of it.

509
00:22:37.400 --> 00:22:38.870
You may not so extenuatehis offence

510
00:22:38.870 --> 00:22:41.430
For I have had such faults;but rather tell me,

511
00:22:41.430 --> 00:22:44.730
When I, that censure him,do so offend,

512
00:22:44.730 --> 00:22:48.130
Let mine own judgmentpattern out my death,

513
00:22:48.600 --> 00:22:56.630
And nothing come inpartial. Sir, he must die.

514
00:22:56.630 --> 00:22:58.770
Be it as your wisdom will.

515
00:22:58.770 --> 00:22:59.670
Where is the provost?

516
00:22:59.670 --> 00:23:01.900
Here, if it like yourhonour.

517
00:23:01.900 --> 00:23:02.800
See that Claudio

518
00:23:02.800 --> 00:23:04.800
Be executed by nineto-morrow morning:

519
00:23:04.800 --> 00:23:07.070
Bring him his confessor,let him be prepared;

520
00:23:07.070 --> 00:23:12.300
For that's the utmost ofhis pilgrimage.

521
00:23:12.300 --> 00:23:15.770
Well, heaven forgive him!and forgive us all!

522
00:23:15.770 --> 00:23:20.530
Some rise by sin, and someby virtue fall:

523
00:23:20.530 --> 00:23:23.200
Some run from brakes ofice, and answer none:

524
00:23:23.200 --> 00:23:27.670
And some condemned for afault alone.

525
00:23:37.600 --> 00:23:39.070
How now, sir! What's yourname?

526
00:23:39.070 --> 00:23:42.570
and what's the matter?

527
00:23:43.730 --> 00:23:45.230
If it Please your honour,

528
00:23:45.230 --> 00:23:49.470
I am the poor duke'sconstable,

529
00:23:49.470 --> 00:23:50.700
and my name is Elbow:

530
00:23:50.700 --> 00:23:52.970
I do lean upon justice,sir,

531
00:23:52.970 --> 00:23:54.930
and do bring in herebefore your good honour

532
00:23:54.930 --> 00:23:57.730
two notorious benefactors.

533
00:23:57.730 --> 00:24:00.170
Benefactors? Well; whatbenefactors are they?

534
00:24:00.170 --> 00:24:02.670
are they not malefactors?

535
00:24:02.670 --> 00:24:04.130
If it? please your honour,

536
00:24:04.130 --> 00:24:05.830
I know not well what theyare:

537
00:24:05.830 --> 00:24:08.230
but precise villains theyare,

538
00:24:08.230 --> 00:24:11.170
that I am sure of; andvoid of all profanation

539
00:24:11.170 --> 00:24:14.630
in the world that goodChristians ought to have.

540
00:24:14.630 --> 00:24:16.900
Here's a wise officer;This comes off well.

541
00:24:16.900 --> 00:24:21.530
Go to: what quality arethey of?

542
00:24:22.370 --> 00:24:26.630
Elbow is your name? whydost thou not speak, Elbow?

543
00:24:26.630 --> 00:24:29.170
He cannot, sir; he's outat elbow.

544
00:24:29.170 --> 00:24:30.870
(laughing)

545
00:24:30.870 --> 00:24:32.870
What are you, sir?

546
00:24:32.870 --> 00:24:37.870
He, sir! a tapster, sir;parcel-bawd;

547
00:24:37.870 --> 00:24:40.930
one that serves a badwoman; whose house, sir,

548
00:24:40.930 --> 00:24:43.800
was, as they say, pluckeddown in the suburbs;

549
00:24:43.800 --> 00:24:47.500
but now she professes ahot-house, which, I believe,

550
00:24:47.500 --> 00:24:50.570
is a very ill house too.

551
00:24:52.270 --> 00:24:54.930
How know you that?

552
00:24:54.930 --> 00:24:59.470
My wife, sir, whom Idetest before heaven

553
00:24:59.470 --> 00:25:01.000
and your honour,--

554
00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:02.200
How? thy wife?

555
00:25:02.200 --> 00:25:05.370
Ay, sir; whom, I thankheaven, is an honest woman,--

556
00:25:05.370 --> 00:25:07.530
Dost thou detest hertherefore?

557
00:25:07.530 --> 00:25:11.000
I say, sir, I will detestmyself also,

558
00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:12.770
as well as she, that thishouse,

559
00:25:12.770 --> 00:25:15.170
if it be not a bawd's house,it is pity of her life,

560
00:25:15.170 --> 00:25:17.100
for it is a naughty house.

561
00:25:17.100 --> 00:25:18.930
How dost thou know that,constable?

562
00:25:18.930 --> 00:25:21.600
Marry, sir, by my wife;

563
00:25:21.600 --> 00:25:24.270
who, if she had been awoman cardinally given,

564
00:25:24.270 --> 00:25:28.230
might have been accused infornication, adultery,

565
00:25:28.230 --> 00:25:31.070
and all kinds ofuncleanliness there.

566
00:25:31.070 --> 00:25:32.500
By the woman's means?

567
00:25:32.500 --> 00:25:34.770
Ay, sir, by MistressOverdone's means:

568
00:25:34.770 --> 00:25:37.000
but as she spit in hisface,

569
00:25:37.000 --> 00:25:38.700
so she defied him.

570
00:25:38.700 --> 00:25:41.670
Sir, if it please yourhonour, this is not so.

571
00:25:41.670 --> 00:25:44.730
Prove it before thesevarlets here,

572
00:25:44.730 --> 00:25:47.170
thou honourable man; proveit.

573
00:25:47.170 --> 00:25:48.800
Do you hear how hemisplaces?

574
00:25:48.800 --> 00:25:52.800
Sir, she came in greatwith child;

575
00:25:52.800 --> 00:25:55.700
and longing, saving yourhonour's reverence,

576
00:25:55.700 --> 00:25:57.470
for stewed prunes;

577
00:25:57.470 --> 00:25:58.870
sir, we had but two in thehouse,

578
00:25:58.870 --> 00:26:01.070
which at that very distanttime stood, as it were,

579
00:26:01.070 --> 00:26:03.970
in a fruit-dish, a dish ofsome three-pence;

580
00:26:03.970 --> 00:26:06.700
your honours have seensuch dishes;

581
00:26:06.700 --> 00:26:08.870
they are not China dishes,but very good dishes,

582
00:26:08.870 --> 00:26:11.000
Go to, go to: no matterfor the dish, sir.

583
00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:12.800
No, indeed, sir,

584
00:26:12.800 --> 00:26:14.370
and having but two in thedish, as I said,

585
00:26:14.370 --> 00:26:18.170
Master Froth here, thisvery man,

586
00:26:18.170 --> 00:26:19.930
having eaten the rest, asI said,

587
00:26:19.930 --> 00:26:22.570
and, as I say, paying forthem very honestly;

588
00:26:22.570 --> 00:26:24.470
for, as you know, MasterFroth,

589
00:26:24.470 --> 00:26:27.130
I could not give youthree-pence again.

590
00:26:27.130 --> 00:26:28.500
No, indeed.

591
00:26:28.500 --> 00:26:31.200
Very well: you being then,

592
00:26:31.200 --> 00:26:33.200
if you be remembered,

593
00:26:33.200 --> 00:26:35.230
cracking the stones of theforesaid prunes,

594
00:26:35.230 --> 00:26:37.930
Come, you are a tediousfool: to the purpose.

595
00:26:37.930 --> 00:26:39.870
What was done to Elbow'swife,

596
00:26:39.870 --> 00:26:41.530
that he hath cause tocomplain of?

597
00:26:41.530 --> 00:26:43.170
Come me to what was doneto her.

598
00:26:43.170 --> 00:26:45.130
Sir, your honour cannotcome to that yet.

599
00:26:45.130 --> 00:26:48.330
No, sir, nor I mean itnot.

600
00:26:48.330 --> 00:26:50.200
Sir, but you shall come toit,

601
00:26:50.200 --> 00:26:51.300
by your honour's leave.

602
00:26:51.300 --> 00:26:55.230
And, I beseech you, lookinto Master Froth here, sir;

603
00:26:55.230 --> 00:27:01.330
a man of four-score pounda year;

604
00:27:01.330 --> 00:27:04.900
whose father died atHallowmas:

605
00:27:04.900 --> 00:27:09.270
was't not at Hallowmas,Master Froth?

606
00:27:09.270 --> 00:27:12.170
All-hallond eve.

607
00:27:12.170 --> 00:27:13.900
This will last out a nightin Russia,

608
00:27:13.900 --> 00:27:15.330
When nights are longestthere:

609
00:27:15.330 --> 00:27:16.300
I'll take my leave.

610
00:27:16.300 --> 00:27:17.700
And leave you to thehearing of the cause;

611
00:27:17.700 --> 00:27:19.900
Hoping you'll find goodcause to whip them all.

612
00:27:19.900 --> 00:27:23.100
I think no less. Goodmorrow to your lordship.

613
00:27:23.100 --> 00:27:24.970
Now, sir, come on:

614
00:27:24.970 --> 00:27:26.930
what was done to Elbow'swife, once more?

615
00:27:26.930 --> 00:27:31.030
Once? there wasnothing done to her once.

616
00:27:31.030 --> 00:27:35.370
I beseech you, sir, ask himwhat this man did to my wife.

617
00:27:35.370 --> 00:27:37.030
I beseech your honour, askme.

618
00:27:37.030 --> 00:27:38.370
Well, sir; what did thisgentleman to her?

619
00:27:38.370 --> 00:27:43.200
I beseech you, sir, lookin this gentleman's face.

620
00:27:43.200 --> 00:27:45.830
Good Master Froth, lookupon his honour;

621
00:27:45.830 --> 00:27:48.870
'tis for a good purpose.

622
00:27:48.870 --> 00:27:51.500
Doth your honour mark hisface?

623
00:27:51.500 --> 00:27:52.300
Ay, sir, very well.

624
00:27:52.300 --> 00:27:53.730
Nay; I beseech you, markit well.

625
00:27:53.730 --> 00:27:54.670
Well, I do so.

626
00:27:54.670 --> 00:27:57.270
Doth your honour see anyharm in his face?

627
00:27:57.270 --> 00:27:58.300
Why, no.

628
00:27:58.300 --> 00:27:59.870
I'll be supposed upon abook,

629
00:27:59.870 --> 00:28:02.570
his face is the worstthing about him.

630
00:28:02.570 --> 00:28:05.300
Very good; if his face bethe worst thing about him,

631
00:28:05.300 --> 00:28:07.900
how could Master Froth do theconstable's wife any harm?

632
00:28:07.900 --> 00:28:11.900
I would know that of yourhonour.

633
00:28:11.900 --> 00:28:15.400
He's in the right. Constable,what say you to it?

634
00:28:15.800 --> 00:28:19.230
First, an it like you,

635
00:28:19.230 --> 00:28:23.070
the house is a respectedhouse;

636
00:28:23.070 --> 00:28:26.470
next, this is a respectedfellow;

637
00:28:26.470 --> 00:28:28.970
and his mistress is arespected woman.

638
00:28:28.970 --> 00:28:30.100
By this hand, sir,

639
00:28:30.100 --> 00:28:32.230
his wife is a morerespected person

640
00:28:32.230 --> 00:28:34.030
than any of us all.

641
00:28:34.030 --> 00:28:37.930
Varlet, thou liest; thouliest, wicked varlet!

642
00:28:37.930 --> 00:28:41.370
the time has yet to comethat she was ever respected.

643
00:28:41.370 --> 00:28:45.700
Prove this, thou wickedHannibal, prove this

644
00:28:45.700 --> 00:28:48.500
or I'll have mine actionof battery on thee.

645
00:28:48.500 --> 00:28:50.330
If he took you a box o'the ear,

646
00:28:50.330 --> 00:28:52.800
you might have your actionof slander too.

647
00:28:52.800 --> 00:28:56.270
Marry, I thank your goodworship for it.

648
00:28:56.270 --> 00:28:58.470
What is't your worship'spleasure

649
00:28:58.470 --> 00:29:01.900
I shall do with thiswicked caitiff?

650
00:29:01.900 --> 00:29:04.370
Truly, officer, because hehath some offences in him

651
00:29:04.370 --> 00:29:09.370
that thou wouldst discoverif thou couldst,

652
00:29:09.370 --> 00:29:13.170
let him continue in his courses,till thou knowest what they are.

653
00:29:13.170 --> 00:29:17.030
Marry, I thank yourworship for it.

654
00:29:17.030 --> 00:29:19.630
Thou seest now, thou varlet,

655
00:29:19.630 --> 00:29:21.630
what's come upon thee:

656
00:29:21.630 --> 00:29:24.700
thou art to continue now,thou varlet;

657
00:29:24.700 --> 00:29:26.500
thou art to continue.

658
00:29:26.500 --> 00:29:27.800
Where were you born,friend?

659
00:29:27.800 --> 00:29:29.170
Here in Vienna, sir.

660
00:29:29.170 --> 00:29:30.400
Are you of fourscorepounds a year?

661
00:29:30.400 --> 00:29:32.600
Yes, an't please you, sir.

662
00:29:32.600 --> 00:29:35.930
So. What trade are you of,sir?

663
00:29:35.930 --> 00:29:39.830
Tapster; a poor widow'stapster.

664
00:29:39.830 --> 00:29:40.670
Your mistress' name?

665
00:29:40.670 --> 00:29:42.530
Mistress Overdone.

666
00:29:42.530 --> 00:29:43.970
Hath she had any more thanone husband?

667
00:29:43.970 --> 00:29:45.900
Nine, sir; Overdone by thelast.

668
00:29:45.900 --> 00:29:48.600
Nine!

669
00:29:48.600 --> 00:29:51.770
Come hither to me, MasterFroth.

670
00:29:51.770 --> 00:29:54.470
Master Froth, I would nothave you acquainted

671
00:29:54.470 --> 00:29:57.200
with tapsters: they willdraw you, Master Froth,

672
00:29:57.200 --> 00:29:58.870
and you will hang them.

673
00:29:58.870 --> 00:30:00.300
Get you gone, and let mehear no more of you.

674
00:30:00.300 --> 00:30:01.870
I thank your worship.

675
00:30:01.870 --> 00:30:03.130
For mine own part,

676
00:30:03.130 --> 00:30:05.370
I never come into any roomin a tap-house,

677
00:30:05.370 --> 00:30:06.670
but I am drawn in.

678
00:30:06.670 --> 00:30:11.330
Well, no more of it,Master Froth: farewell.

679
00:30:12.770 --> 00:30:16.670
Come you hither to me,Master tapster.

680
00:30:16.670 --> 00:30:17.730
What's your name, Mastertapster?

681
00:30:17.730 --> 00:30:18.500
Pompey.

682
00:30:18.500 --> 00:30:19.330
What else?

683
00:30:19.330 --> 00:30:20.470
Bum, sir.

684
00:30:20.470 --> 00:30:24.470
Troth, and your bum is thegreatest thing about you;

685
00:30:25.170 --> 00:30:28.730
so that in the beastliestsense you are

686
00:30:28.730 --> 00:30:31.970
Pompey the Great. Pompey,

687
00:30:31.970 --> 00:30:34.030
you are partly a bawd,Pompey,

688
00:30:34.030 --> 00:30:35.870
howsoever you colour it inbeing a tapster,

689
00:30:35.870 --> 00:30:38.300
are you not? come, tell metrue:

690
00:30:38.300 --> 00:30:40.100
it shall be the better foryou.

691
00:30:40.100 --> 00:30:43.070
Truly, sir, I am a poorfellow who would live.

692
00:30:43.070 --> 00:30:45.470
How would you live,Pompey? by being a bawd?

693
00:30:45.470 --> 00:30:48.770
What do you think of thetrade, Pompey?

694
00:30:48.770 --> 00:30:50.100
is it a lawful trade?

695
00:30:50.100 --> 00:30:51.770
If the law would allow it,sir.

696
00:30:51.770 --> 00:30:53.970
But the law will not allowit, Pompey;

697
00:30:53.970 --> 00:30:55.530
nor it shall not beallowed in Vienna.

698
00:30:55.530 --> 00:30:59.500
Does your worship mean togeld and splay

699
00:30:59.500 --> 00:31:00.930
all the youth of the city?

700
00:31:00.930 --> 00:31:02.100
No, Pompey.

701
00:31:02.100 --> 00:31:04.930
Truly, sir, in my pooropinion, they will to't then.

702
00:31:04.930 --> 00:31:06.670
If your worship will takeorder

703
00:31:06.670 --> 00:31:08.930
for the drabs and theknaves,

704
00:31:08.930 --> 00:31:11.270
you need not to fear thebawds.

705
00:31:11.270 --> 00:31:14.330
There are pretty ordersbeginning, I can tell you:

706
00:31:14.330 --> 00:31:17.070
it is but heading andhanging.

707
00:31:17.070 --> 00:31:20.670
If you head and hang allthat offend that way

708
00:31:20.670 --> 00:31:22.300
but for ten year together,

709
00:31:22.300 --> 00:31:25.770
you'll be glad to give out acommission for more heads:

710
00:31:25.770 --> 00:31:27.730
if this law hold in Viennaten year,

711
00:31:27.730 --> 00:31:31.700
I'll rent the fairest house init after three-pence a bay:

712
00:31:31.700 --> 00:31:35.200
if you live to see thiscome to pass,

713
00:31:35.200 --> 00:31:37.670
say Pompey told you so.

714
00:31:37.670 --> 00:31:39.470
Thank you, good Pompey;

715
00:31:39.470 --> 00:31:44.000
and, in requital of yourprophecy, hark you:

716
00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:48.400
I advise you, let me notfind you before me again

717
00:31:48.400 --> 00:31:49.700
upon any complaintwhatsoever;

718
00:31:49.700 --> 00:31:52.400
no, not for dwelling whereyou do:

719
00:31:52.400 --> 00:31:54.630
if I do, Pompey,

720
00:31:54.630 --> 00:31:56.370
I shall beat you to yourtent,

721
00:31:56.370 --> 00:31:58.530
and prove a shrewd Caesarto you;

722
00:31:58.530 --> 00:32:01.930
in plain dealing, Pompey,I shall have you whipt:

723
00:32:01.930 --> 00:32:04.270
so, for this time, Pompey,fare you well.

724
00:32:05.300 --> 00:32:09.830
I thank your worship foryour good counsel:

725
00:32:12.800 --> 00:32:15.400
but I shall follow it asthe flesh and fortune

726
00:32:15.400 --> 00:32:17.400
shall better determine.

727
00:32:17.400 --> 00:32:21.000
Whip me? No, no; letcarman whip his jade:

728
00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:26.130
The valiant heart is notwhipt out of his trade.

729
00:32:26.130 --> 00:32:29.400
Come hither to me, MasterElbow;

730
00:32:29.400 --> 00:32:32.600
come hither, Masterconstable.

731
00:32:32.600 --> 00:32:34.500
How long have you been inthis place of constable?

732
00:32:34.500 --> 00:32:36.170
Seven year and a half,sir.

733
00:32:36.170 --> 00:32:38.770
I thought, by yourreadiness in the office,

734
00:32:38.770 --> 00:32:41.570
you had continued in itsome time.

735
00:32:41.570 --> 00:32:42.730
You say, seven yearstogether?

736
00:32:42.730 --> 00:32:44.000
And a half, sir.

737
00:32:44.000 --> 00:32:46.470
Alas, it hath been greatpains to you.

738
00:32:46.470 --> 00:32:50.230
They do you wrong to putyou so oft upon 't:

739
00:32:50.230 --> 00:32:52.700
are there not men in yourward sufficient to serve it?

740
00:32:52.700 --> 00:32:56.070
Faith, sir, few of any witin such matters:

741
00:32:56.070 --> 00:32:57.300
as they are chosen,

742
00:32:57.300 --> 00:32:59.530
they are glad to choose mefor them;

743
00:32:59.530 --> 00:33:01.630
I do it for some piece ofmoney,

744
00:33:01.630 --> 00:33:03.070
and go through with all.

745
00:33:03.070 --> 00:33:07.370
Look you bring me in thenames of some six or seven,

746
00:33:07.370 --> 00:33:08.930
the most sufficient ofyour parish.

747
00:33:08.930 --> 00:33:11.900
To your worship's house,sir?

748
00:33:11.900 --> 00:33:13.330
To my house. Fare youwell.

749
00:33:22.200 --> 00:33:24.830
I pray you home to dinnerwith me.

750
00:33:24.830 --> 00:33:27.900
I humbly thank you.

751
00:33:27.900 --> 00:33:33.030
It grieves me for thedeath of Claudio;

752
00:33:33.030 --> 00:33:35.200
But there's no remedy.

753
00:33:35.200 --> 00:33:37.330
Lord Angelo is severe.

754
00:33:37.330 --> 00:33:40.100
It is but needful:

755
00:33:40.100 --> 00:33:43.700
Mercy is not itself, thatoft looks so;

756
00:33:43.700 --> 00:33:47.070
Pardon is still the nurseof second woe:

757
00:33:47.070 --> 00:33:50.830
But yet,--poor Claudio!

758
00:33:55.370 --> 00:33:58.330
Is it your will Claudioshall die tomorrow?

759
00:33:58.330 --> 00:34:03.600
Did not I tell thee yea?hadst thou not order?

760
00:34:03.800 --> 00:34:06.930
Why dost thou ask again?

761
00:34:06.930 --> 00:34:09.900
Lest I might be too rash:

762
00:34:09.900 --> 00:34:12.230
Under your goodcorrection, I have seen,

763
00:34:12.230 --> 00:34:13.670
When, after execution,

764
00:34:13.670 --> 00:34:15.830
judgment hath repentedo'er his doom.

765
00:34:15.830 --> 00:34:17.970
Go to; let that be mine:

766
00:34:17.970 --> 00:34:20.870
Do you your office, orgive up your place,

767
00:34:20.870 --> 00:34:22.500
And you shall well bespared.

768
00:34:22.500 --> 00:34:25.330
I crave your honour'spardon.

769
00:34:25.330 --> 00:34:27.630
What shall be done, sir,with the groaning Juliet?

770
00:34:27.630 --> 00:34:29.100
She's very near her hour.

771
00:34:29.100 --> 00:34:30.130
Dispose of her

772
00:34:30.130 --> 00:34:33.100
To some more fitter place,and that with speed.

773
00:34:33.100 --> 00:34:35.070
Here is the sister of theman condemn'd

774
00:34:35.070 --> 00:34:36.930
Desires access to you.

775
00:34:36.930 --> 00:34:38.030
Hath he a sister?

776
00:34:38.030 --> 00:34:41.870
Ay, my good lord; a veryvirtuous maid,

777
00:34:41.870 --> 00:34:43.530
And to be shortly of asisterhood,

778
00:34:43.530 --> 00:34:45.170
If not already.

779
00:34:45.170 --> 00:34:47.930
Well, let her be admitted.

780
00:34:48.800 --> 00:34:50.330
See you the fornicatressbe removed:

781
00:34:50.330 --> 00:34:52.500
Let have needful, but notlavish, means;

782
00:34:52.500 --> 00:34:55.000
There shall be orderfor't.

783
00:34:57.030 --> 00:34:59.200
You're welcome:

784
00:35:03.730 --> 00:35:05.630
what's your will?

785
00:35:05.630 --> 00:35:07.370
I am a woeful suitor toyour honour,

786
00:35:07.370 --> 00:35:09.130
Please but your honourhear me.

787
00:35:09.130 --> 00:35:11.570
Well; what's your suit?

788
00:35:11.570 --> 00:35:14.200
There is a vice that mostI do abhor,

789
00:35:14.200 --> 00:35:16.570
And most desire shouldmeet the blow of justice;

790
00:35:16.570 --> 00:35:19.500
For which I would notplead, but that I must;

791
00:35:19.500 --> 00:35:20.770
For which I must notplead,

792
00:35:20.770 --> 00:35:23.100
but that I am at war'twixt will and will not.

793
00:35:23.100 --> 00:35:24.630
Well; the matter?

794
00:35:24.630 --> 00:35:29.600
I have a brother iscondemn'd to die:

795
00:35:29.600 --> 00:35:31.300
I do beseech you, let itbe his fault,

796
00:35:31.300 --> 00:35:35.770
And not my brother.

797
00:35:35.770 --> 00:35:38.500
Condemn the fault and notthe actor of it?

798
00:35:38.500 --> 00:35:43.000
Why, every fault'scondemn'd ere it be done:

799
00:35:43.000 --> 00:35:44.730
Mine were the very cipherof a function,

800
00:35:44.730 --> 00:35:47.200
To fine the faults whosefine stands in record,

801
00:35:47.200 --> 00:35:50.100
And let go by the actor.

802
00:35:50.100 --> 00:35:53.470
O just but severe law!

803
00:35:53.470 --> 00:35:58.370
I had a brother, then.Heaven keep your honour!

804
00:35:58.370 --> 00:36:02.470
Give't not o'er so: to himagain, entreat him;

805
00:36:02.470 --> 00:36:06.530
Kneel down before him,hang upon his gown:

806
00:36:06.530 --> 00:36:08.670
You are too cold; if youshould need a pin,

807
00:36:08.670 --> 00:36:10.930
You could not with moretame a tongue desire it:

808
00:36:10.930 --> 00:36:12.130
To him, I say!

809
00:36:12.130 --> 00:36:13.670
Must he needs die?

810
00:36:13.670 --> 00:36:15.430
Maiden, no remedy.

811
00:36:15.430 --> 00:36:17.400
Yes; I do think that youmight pardon him,

812
00:36:17.400 --> 00:36:20.370
And neither heaven nor mangrieve at the mercy.

813
00:36:20.370 --> 00:36:21.100
I will not do't.

814
00:36:21.100 --> 00:36:22.800
But can you, if you would?

815
00:36:22.800 --> 00:36:25.170
Look, what I will not,that I cannot do.

816
00:36:25.170 --> 00:36:27.600
But might you do't, and dothe world no wrong,

817
00:36:27.600 --> 00:36:29.600
If so your heart weretouch'd with that remorse

818
00:36:29.600 --> 00:36:31.470
A s mine is to him?

819
00:36:31.470 --> 00:36:33.200
He's sentenced; 'tis toolate.

820
00:36:33.200 --> 00:36:34.430
You are too cold.

821
00:36:34.430 --> 00:36:37.200
Too late? why, no; I, thatdo speak a word.

822
00:36:37.200 --> 00:36:39.730
May call it back again.

823
00:36:39.730 --> 00:36:42.570
Well, believe this,

824
00:36:42.570 --> 00:36:44.530
No ceremony that to greatones 'longs,

825
00:36:44.530 --> 00:36:47.500
Not the king's crown, northe deputed sword,

826
00:36:47.500 --> 00:36:50.100
The marshal's truncheon,nor the judge's robe,

827
00:36:50.100 --> 00:36:53.030
Become them with one halfso good a grace

828
00:36:53.030 --> 00:36:56.400
As mercy does.

829
00:36:56.400 --> 00:37:00.770
If he had been as you andyou as he,

830
00:37:00.770 --> 00:37:04.570
You would have slipt likehim; but he, like you,

831
00:37:04.570 --> 00:37:06.170
Would not have been sostern.

832
00:37:06.170 --> 00:37:07.270
Pray you, be gone.

833
00:37:07.270 --> 00:37:09.030
I would to heaven I hadyour potency,

834
00:37:09.030 --> 00:37:11.270
And you were Isabel!should it then be thus?

835
00:37:11.270 --> 00:37:13.570
No; I would tell what'twere to be a judge,

836
00:37:13.570 --> 00:37:14.930
And what a prisoner.

837
00:37:14.930 --> 00:37:16.970
Ay, touch him; there's thevein.

838
00:37:16.970 --> 00:37:20.270
Your brother is a forfeitof the law,

839
00:37:20.270 --> 00:37:22.030
And you but waste yourwords.

840
00:37:22.030 --> 00:37:23.100
Alas, alas!

841
00:37:23.100 --> 00:37:27.200
Why, all the souls thatwere were forfeit once;

842
00:37:27.200 --> 00:37:29.270
And He that might thevantage best have took

843
00:37:29.270 --> 00:37:32.270
Found out the remedy.

844
00:37:32.270 --> 00:37:33.270
How would you be,

845
00:37:33.270 --> 00:37:35.070
If He, which is the top ofjudgment,

846
00:37:35.070 --> 00:37:39.800
should but judge you asyou are?

847
00:37:39.800 --> 00:37:40.830
O, think on that;

848
00:37:40.830 --> 00:37:42.930
And mercy then willbreathe within your lips,

849
00:37:42.930 --> 00:37:45.570
Like man new made.

850
00:37:45.570 --> 00:37:49.200
Be you content, fair maid;

851
00:37:49.200 --> 00:37:54.370
It is the law, not Icondemn your brother:

852
00:37:54.370 --> 00:37:56.030
Were he my kinsman,brother, or my son,

853
00:37:56.030 --> 00:38:00.200
It should be thus withhim: he must die tomorrow.

854
00:38:00.200 --> 00:38:03.400
To-morrow! O, that'ssudden!

855
00:38:03.400 --> 00:38:04.570
Spare him, spare him!

856
00:38:04.570 --> 00:38:07.530
He's not prepared fordeath.

857
00:38:07.530 --> 00:38:12.270
Even for our kitchens wekill the fowl of season:

858
00:38:12.270 --> 00:38:14.870
shall we serve heaven withless respect

859
00:38:14.870 --> 00:38:20.330
than we do minister to ourgross selves?

860
00:38:20.330 --> 00:38:24.570
Good, good my lord,bethink you;

861
00:38:24.570 --> 00:38:28.100
Who is it that hath diedfor this offence?

862
00:38:28.100 --> 00:38:29.800
There's many havecommitted it.

863
00:38:29.800 --> 00:38:31.800
Ay, well said.

864
00:38:31.800 --> 00:38:38.130
The law hath not been dead,though it hath slept:

865
00:38:39.130 --> 00:38:41.370
Those many had not daredto do that evil,

866
00:38:41.370 --> 00:38:42.800
If the first that did theedict infringe

867
00:38:42.800 --> 00:38:45.330
Had answer'd for his deed:

868
00:38:45.330 --> 00:38:48.800
now 'tis awake takes noteof what is done;

869
00:38:48.800 --> 00:38:50.400
and, like a prophet,

870
00:38:50.400 --> 00:38:52.770
Looks in a glass, thatshows what future evils,

871
00:38:52.770 --> 00:38:54.600
Either new, or byremissness new-conceived,

872
00:38:54.600 --> 00:38:56.770
And so in progress to behatch'd and born,

873
00:38:56.770 --> 00:39:00.600
Are now to have nosuccessive degrees,

874
00:39:00.600 --> 00:39:03.400
But, ere they live, toend.

875
00:39:03.400 --> 00:39:05.430
Yet show some pity.

876
00:39:05.430 --> 00:39:08.600
I show it most of all whenI show justice;

877
00:39:08.600 --> 00:39:13.000
For then I pity those I donot know,

878
00:39:13.000 --> 00:39:15.870
Which a dismiss'd offencewould after gall;

879
00:39:15.870 --> 00:39:19.970
And do him right that,answering one foul wrong,

880
00:39:19.970 --> 00:39:27.630
Lives not to act another.Be satisfied;

881
00:39:27.630 --> 00:39:34.000
Your brother diesto-morrow; be content.

882
00:39:37.830 --> 00:39:40.530
So you must be the firstthat gives this sentence,

883
00:39:40.530 --> 00:39:43.670
And he, that suffer's.

884
00:39:43.670 --> 00:39:44.970
O, it is excellent

885
00:39:44.970 --> 00:39:46.000
To have a giant'sstrength;

886
00:39:46.000 --> 00:39:48.730
but it is tyrannous to useit like a giant.

887
00:39:48.730 --> 00:39:50.630
That's well said.

888
00:39:50.630 --> 00:39:52.030
Could great men thunder

889
00:39:52.030 --> 00:39:55.930
As Jove himself does, Jovewould ne'er be quiet,

890
00:39:55.930 --> 00:39:57.270
For every pelting, pettyofficer

891
00:39:57.270 --> 00:39:59.000
Would use his heaven forthunder;

892
00:39:59.000 --> 00:40:02.770
Nothing but thunder!

893
00:40:03.230 --> 00:40:04.630
Merciful Heaven,

894
00:40:04.630 --> 00:40:07.500
Thou rather with thy sharpand sulphurous bolt

895
00:40:07.500 --> 00:40:09.230
Split'st the unwedgeableand gnarled oak

896
00:40:09.230 --> 00:40:13.630
Than the soft myrtle: butman, proud man,

897
00:40:13.630 --> 00:40:16.300
Drest in a little briefauthority,

898
00:40:16.300 --> 00:40:18.830
Most ignorant of what he'smost assured,

899
00:40:18.830 --> 00:40:21.400
His glassy essence, likean angry ape,

900
00:40:21.400 --> 00:40:24.700
Plays such fantastictricks before high heaven

901
00:40:24.700 --> 00:40:27.770
As make the angels weep;

902
00:40:27.770 --> 00:40:29.470
who, with our spleens,

903
00:40:29.470 --> 00:40:32.500
Would all themselves laughmortal.

904
00:40:32.500 --> 00:40:35.100
O, to him, to him, wench!he will relent;

905
00:40:35.100 --> 00:40:36.530
He's coming; I perceive 't.

906
00:40:36.530 --> 00:40:40.570
We cannot weigh ourbrother with ourself:

907
00:40:40.570 --> 00:40:46.030
Great men may jest withsaints; 'tis wit in them,

908
00:40:46.030 --> 00:40:48.600
But in the less foulprofanation.

909
00:40:48.600 --> 00:40:51.000
Thou'rt i' the right,girl; more o, that.

910
00:40:51.000 --> 00:40:54.100
That in the captain's buta choleric word,

911
00:40:54.100 --> 00:40:57.830
Which in the soldier isflat blasphemy.

912
00:40:57.830 --> 00:41:02.070
Art avised o' that? moreon 't.

913
00:41:02.070 --> 00:41:05.300
Why do you put thesesayings upon me?

914
00:41:05.300 --> 00:41:07.470
Because authority, thoughit err like others,

915
00:41:07.470 --> 00:41:09.530
Hath yet a kind ofmedicine in itself,

916
00:41:09.530 --> 00:41:13.430
That skins the vice o' thetop.

917
00:41:13.430 --> 00:41:15.930
Go to your bosom;

918
00:41:15.930 --> 00:41:18.300
Knock there, and ask yourheart

919
00:41:18.300 --> 00:41:19.270
what it doth know

920
00:41:19.270 --> 00:41:21.300
That's like my brother'sfault:

921
00:41:21.300 --> 00:41:25.430
if it confess a naturalguiltiness such as is his,

922
00:41:25.430 --> 00:41:28.400
Let it not sound a thoughtupon your tongue

923
00:41:28.400 --> 00:41:30.430
Against my brother's life.

924
00:41:34.600 --> 00:41:36.530
She speaks, and 'tis suchsense,

925
00:41:36.530 --> 00:41:40.400
that my sense breathes with it.

926
00:41:42.530 --> 00:41:44.230
Fare ye well.

927
00:41:44.230 --> 00:41:47.600
Gentle my lord, turn back.

928
00:41:51.730 --> 00:41:59.930
I will bethink me: comeagain tomorrow.

929
00:41:59.930 --> 00:42:05.070
Hark how I'll bribe you:good my lord, turn back.

930
00:42:06.570 --> 00:42:09.030
How! bribe me?

931
00:42:09.030 --> 00:42:11.430
Ay, with such gifts thatheaven shall share with you.

932
00:42:11.430 --> 00:42:14.200
Not with fond shekels ofthe tested gold,

933
00:42:14.200 --> 00:42:16.700
Or stones whose rates areeither rich or poor

934
00:42:16.700 --> 00:42:17.870
As fancy values them;

935
00:42:17.870 --> 00:42:20.170
but with true prayers

936
00:42:20.170 --> 00:42:22.030
That shall be up at heavenand enter there

937
00:42:22.030 --> 00:42:26.870
Ere sun-rise, prayers frompreserved souls,

938
00:42:26.870 --> 00:42:29.430
From fasting maids whoseminds are dedicate

939
00:42:29.430 --> 00:42:33.430
To nothing temporal.

940
00:42:33.430 --> 00:42:39.230
Well; come to meto-morrow.

941
00:42:39.230 --> 00:42:41.430
Go to; 'tis well; away!

942
00:42:41.430 --> 00:42:43.130
Heaven keep your honoursafe!

943
00:42:43.130 --> 00:42:47.000
Amen: For I am that waygoing to temptation,

944
00:42:47.000 --> 00:42:49.630
Where prayers cross.

945
00:42:49.630 --> 00:42:50.700
At what hour to-morrow

946
00:42:50.700 --> 00:42:52.400
Shall I attend yourlordship?

947
00:42:52.400 --> 00:42:56.100
At any time 'fore noon.

948
00:42:56.100 --> 00:42:58.930
'Save your honour!

949
00:43:03.800 --> 00:43:09.930
From thee, even from thyvirtue!

950
00:43:09.930 --> 00:43:12.430
What's this, what's this?

951
00:43:12.430 --> 00:43:15.330
Is this her fault or mine?

952
00:43:15.330 --> 00:43:19.000
The tempter or thetempted, who sins most?

953
00:43:19.000 --> 00:43:26.230
Ha!

954
00:43:26.900 --> 00:43:31.030
Not she: nor doth shetempt: but it is I

955
00:43:31.030 --> 00:43:32.570
That, lying by the violetin the sun,

956
00:43:32.570 --> 00:43:34.400
Do as the carrion does,not as the flower,

957
00:43:34.400 --> 00:43:37.930
Corrupt with virtuousseason.

958
00:43:37.930 --> 00:43:39.600
Can it be that modesty maymore betray our sense

959
00:43:39.600 --> 00:43:41.570
Than woman's lightness?

960
00:43:41.570 --> 00:43:43.130
Having waste groundenough,

961
00:43:43.130 --> 00:43:44.870
Shall we desire to razethe sanctuary

962
00:43:44.870 --> 00:43:51.630
And pitch our evils there?O, fie, fie, fie!

963
00:43:51.630 --> 00:43:58.530
What dost thou, or whatart thou, Angelo?

964
00:43:58.530 --> 00:44:01.430
Dost thou desire herfoully for those things

965
00:44:01.430 --> 00:44:10.270
That make her good? O, lether brother live!

966
00:44:10.270 --> 00:44:11.530
Thieves for their robberyhave authority

967
00:44:11.530 --> 00:44:16.370
When judges stealthemselves.

968
00:44:17.230 --> 00:44:22.570
What, do I love her,

969
00:44:22.570 --> 00:44:25.570
That I desire to hear herspeak again,

970
00:44:25.570 --> 00:44:30.000
And feast upon her eyes?

971
00:44:30.000 --> 00:44:35.500
What is't I dream on?

972
00:44:35.500 --> 00:44:37.570
O cunning enemy, that, tocatch a saint,

973
00:44:37.570 --> 00:44:40.470
With saints dost bait thyhook!

974
00:44:40.470 --> 00:44:42.930
Most dangerous is thattemptation that doth goad us on

975
00:44:42.930 --> 00:44:46.100
To sin in loving virtue:never could the strumpet,

976
00:44:46.100 --> 00:44:48.030
With all her doublevigour, art and nature,

977
00:44:48.030 --> 00:44:53.370
Once stir my temper; butthis virtuous maid

978
00:44:53.370 --> 00:44:57.470
Subdues me quite.

979
00:45:02.130 --> 00:45:03.870
Even till now,

980
00:45:03.870 --> 00:45:12.870
When men were fond, Ismiled and wonder'd how.

981
00:45:33.270 --> 00:45:35.230
Bound by my charity and myblest order,

982
00:45:35.230 --> 00:45:37.070
I come to visit theafflicted spirits

983
00:45:37.070 --> 00:45:39.070
Here in the prison. Do methe common right

984
00:45:39.070 --> 00:45:40.570
To let me see them and tomake me know

985
00:45:40.570 --> 00:45:42.030
The nature of theircrimes,

986
00:45:42.030 --> 00:45:44.100
that I may minister tothem accordingly.

987
00:45:44.100 --> 00:45:47.230
I would do more than that,if more were needful.

988
00:45:47.230 --> 00:45:50.470
Look, here's agentlewoman of mine,

989
00:45:50.470 --> 00:45:52.630
Who, falling in the flawsof her own youth,

990
00:45:52.630 --> 00:45:56.730
Hath blister'd her report:she is with child;

991
00:45:56.730 --> 00:45:58.270
And he that got it,sentenced;

992
00:45:58.270 --> 00:46:01.000
a young man more fit to doanother such offence

993
00:46:01.000 --> 00:46:02.470
Than die for this.

994
00:46:02.470 --> 00:46:03.830
When must he die?

995
00:46:03.830 --> 00:46:06.330
As I do think, to-morrow.

996
00:46:10.730 --> 00:46:13.570
I have provided for you:stay awhile,

997
00:46:13.570 --> 00:46:15.770
And you shall beconducted.

998
00:46:20.300 --> 00:46:22.700
Repent you, fair one, ofthe sin you carry?

999
00:46:22.700 --> 00:46:26.030
I do; and bear the shamemost patiently.

1000
00:46:26.030 --> 00:46:27.870
I'll teach you how you shallarraign your conscience,

1001
00:46:27.870 --> 00:46:29.930
And try your penitence, ifit be sound,

1002
00:46:29.930 --> 00:46:31.530
Or hollowly put on.

1003
00:46:31.530 --> 00:46:33.300
I'll gladly learn.

1004
00:46:33.300 --> 00:46:34.930
Love you the man thatwrong'd you?

1005
00:46:34.930 --> 00:46:38.530
Yes, as I love the womanthat wrong'd him.

1006
00:46:38.530 --> 00:46:40.130
So then it seems your mostoffenceful act

1007
00:46:40.130 --> 00:46:42.770
Was mutually committed?

1008
00:46:42.770 --> 00:46:44.100
Mutually.

1009
00:46:44.100 --> 00:46:46.770
Then was your sin ofheavier kind than his.

1010
00:46:46.770 --> 00:46:49.800
I do confess it, andrepent it, father.

1011
00:46:49.800 --> 00:46:52.170
'Tis meet so, daughter:but lest you do repent,

1012
00:46:52.170 --> 00:46:54.930
As that the sin hathbrought you to this shame,

1013
00:46:54.930 --> 00:46:56.870
Which sorrow is always towardsourselves, not heaven,

1014
00:46:56.870 --> 00:47:00.570
Showing we would not spareheaven as we love it,

1015
00:47:00.570 --> 00:47:02.330
But as we stand in fear,

1016
00:47:02.330 --> 00:47:04.070
I do repent me, as it isan evil,

1017
00:47:04.070 --> 00:47:05.530
And take the shame withjoy.

1018
00:47:05.530 --> 00:47:07.570
There rest.

1019
00:47:07.570 --> 00:47:12.170
Your partner, as I hear,must die to-morrow,

1020
00:47:12.170 --> 00:47:16.000
And I am going withinstruction to him.

1021
00:47:16.000 --> 00:47:19.000
Grace go with you,Benedicite!

1022
00:47:24.730 --> 00:47:29.530
Must die to-morrow! Oinjurious love,

1023
00:47:29.530 --> 00:47:31.170
That respites me a life,

1024
00:47:31.170 --> 00:47:37.700
whose very comfort isstill a dying horror!

1025
00:47:43.330 --> 00:47:48.070
When I would pray andthink, I think and pray

1026
00:47:48.070 --> 00:47:55.030
To several subjects. Heavenhath my empty words;

1027
00:47:55.030 --> 00:47:56.930
Whilst my invention,

1028
00:47:56.930 --> 00:48:00.370
hearing not my tongue,

1029
00:48:00.370 --> 00:48:07.030
Anchors on Isabel:

1030
00:48:07.030 --> 00:48:08.030
Heaven in my mouth,

1031
00:48:08.030 --> 00:48:10.270
As if I did but only chewhis name;

1032
00:48:10.270 --> 00:48:15.930
And in my heart the strongand swelling evil

1033
00:48:16.400 --> 00:48:19.200
Of my conception.

1034
00:48:22.900 --> 00:48:25.970
The state, whereon Istudied

1035
00:48:25.970 --> 00:48:28.300
Is like a good thing,being often read,

1036
00:48:28.300 --> 00:48:35.230
Grown fear'd and tedious;yea, my gravity,

1037
00:48:35.230 --> 00:48:37.930
Wherein--let no man hearme--I take pride,

1038
00:48:37.930 --> 00:48:40.300
Could I with boot changefor an idle plume,

1039
00:48:40.300 --> 00:48:42.770
Which the air beats forvain.

1040
00:48:44.200 --> 00:48:50.730
O place, O form,

1041
00:48:50.730 --> 00:48:53.130
How often dost thou withthy case, thy habit,

1042
00:48:53.130 --> 00:48:56.030
Wrench awe from fools andtie the wiser souls

1043
00:48:56.030 --> 00:49:00.270
To thy false seeming!

1044
00:49:00.270 --> 00:49:06.270
Blood, thou art blood:

1045
00:49:06.270 --> 00:49:08.370
Let's write good angel onthe devil's horn:

1046
00:49:08.370 --> 00:49:10.270
'Tis not the devil'screst.

1047
00:49:10.270 --> 00:49:13.400
