Come your way, sir. 'Blessyou, good father friar.

1556
01:15:13.570 --> 01:15:14.900
And you, good brotherfather.

1557
01:15:14.900 --> 01:15:17.030
What offence hath this manmade you, sir?

1558
01:15:17.030 --> 01:15:19.170
Marry, sir, he hathoffended the law:

1559
01:15:19.170 --> 01:15:21.270
and, sir, we take him tobe a thief too, sir;

1560
01:15:21.270 --> 01:15:23.300
for we have found upon him

1561
01:15:23.300 --> 01:15:25.330
a strange picklock,

1562
01:15:25.330 --> 01:15:27.900
which we have sent to thedeputy.

1563
01:15:27.900 --> 01:15:30.500
Fie, sirrah! a bawd, awicked bawd!

1564
01:15:30.500 --> 01:15:32.200
The evil that thou causestto be done,

1565
01:15:32.200 --> 01:15:33.730
That is thy means to live.

1566
01:15:33.730 --> 01:15:34.970
Do thou but think

1567
01:15:34.970 --> 01:15:36.930
What 'tis to cram a maw orclothe a back

1568
01:15:36.930 --> 01:15:38.800
From such a filthy vice:

1569
01:15:38.800 --> 01:15:39.730
say to thyself,

1570
01:15:39.730 --> 01:15:41.670
From their abominable andbeastly touches

1571
01:15:41.670 --> 01:15:45.030
I drink, I eat, arraymyself, and live.

1572
01:15:45.030 --> 01:15:47.130
Canst thou believe thyliving is a life,

1573
01:15:47.130 --> 01:15:48.500
So stinkingly depending?Go mend, go mend.

1574
01:15:48.500 --> 01:15:53.200
Indeed, it does stink insome sort, sir;

1575
01:15:53.200 --> 01:15:55.070
but yet, sir, I wouldprove--

1576
01:15:55.070 --> 01:15:57.270
Nay, if the devil havegiven thee proofs for sin,

1577
01:15:57.270 --> 01:15:58.830
Thou wilt prove his.

1578
01:15:58.830 --> 01:16:00.300
Take him to prison,officer:

1579
01:16:00.300 --> 01:16:02.200
Correction and instructionmust both work

1580
01:16:02.200 --> 01:16:04.130
Ere this rude beast willprofit.

1581
01:16:04.130 --> 01:16:05.200
He must before the deputy,sir;

1582
01:16:05.200 --> 01:16:06.330
he has given him warning:

1583
01:16:06.330 --> 01:16:09.070
the deputy cannot abide awhoremaster:

1584
01:16:09.070 --> 01:16:10.030
if he be a whoremonger,

1585
01:16:10.030 --> 01:16:10.970
and comes before him,

1586
01:16:10.970 --> 01:16:13.170
he were as good go a mileon his errand.

1587
01:16:13.170 --> 01:16:16.770
His neck will come to yourwaist,--a cord, sir.

1588
01:16:16.770 --> 01:16:18.670
I spy comfort; I cry bail.

1589
01:16:18.670 --> 01:16:22.270
Here's a gentleman and afriend of mine.

1590
01:16:22.270 --> 01:16:27.270
How now, noble Pompey!

1591
01:16:27.270 --> 01:16:29.300
What, at the wheels ofCaesar?

1592
01:16:29.300 --> 01:16:33.430
art thou led in triumph?

1593
01:16:33.430 --> 01:16:36.170
What, is there none ofPygmalion's images,

1594
01:16:36.170 --> 01:16:39.000
newly made woman, to behad now,

1595
01:16:39.000 --> 01:16:40.700
for putting the hand inthe pocket

1596
01:16:40.700 --> 01:16:45.600
and extracting itclutch'd?

1597
01:16:45.600 --> 01:16:46.730
What sayest thou, Trot?

1598
01:16:46.730 --> 01:16:48.670
Is the world as it was,man?

1599
01:16:48.670 --> 01:16:52.670
Which is the way? Is itsad, and few words? or how?

1600
01:16:52.670 --> 01:16:53.630
The trick of it?

1601
01:16:53.630 --> 01:16:55.970
Still thus, and thus;still worse!

1602
01:16:55.970 --> 01:16:57.930
How doth my dear morsel,thy mistress?

1603
01:16:57.930 --> 01:16:59.630
Procures she still, ha?

1604
01:16:59.630 --> 01:17:01.670
Troth, sir, she hath eatenup all her beef,

1605
01:17:01.670 --> 01:17:03.870
she is herself in the tub.

1606
01:17:03.870 --> 01:17:05.830
Why, 'tis good; it is theright of it;

1607
01:17:05.830 --> 01:17:07.400
it must be so:

1608
01:17:07.400 --> 01:17:10.600
ever your fresh whore andyour powdered bawd:

1609
01:17:10.600 --> 01:17:13.930
an unshunned consequence;it must be so.

1610
01:17:13.930 --> 01:17:15.400
Art going to prison,Pompey?

1611
01:17:15.400 --> 01:17:17.630
Yes, faith, sir.

1612
01:17:17.630 --> 01:17:19.800
Why, 'tis not amiss,Pompey.

1613
01:17:19.800 --> 01:17:23.230
Farewell: go, say I sentthee thither.

1614
01:17:23.230 --> 01:17:25.270
For debt, Pompey? or how?

1615
01:17:25.270 --> 01:17:27.630
For being a bawd, forbeing a bawd.

1616
01:17:27.630 --> 01:17:29.570
Well, then, imprison him:

1617
01:17:29.570 --> 01:17:31.770
if imprisonment be the dueof a bawd,

1618
01:17:31.770 --> 01:17:36.130
why, 'tis his right: bawdis he doubtless,

1619
01:17:36.130 --> 01:17:40.730
and of antiquity too;bawd-born.

1620
01:17:40.730 --> 01:17:44.570
Farewell, good Pompey.

1621
01:17:47.800 --> 01:17:50.930
Commend me to the prison,Pompey:

1622
01:17:50.930 --> 01:17:53.330
you will turn good husbandnow, Pompey;

1623
01:17:53.330 --> 01:17:55.500
you will keep the house.

1624
01:17:55.500 --> 01:17:59.800
Sir, I hope your goodworship will be my bail.

1625
01:17:59.800 --> 01:18:02.430
No, indeed, will I not,Pompey;

1626
01:18:02.430 --> 01:18:04.130
it is not the wear.

1627
01:18:04.130 --> 01:18:08.100
I will pray, Pompey, toincrease your bondage:

1628
01:18:08.100 --> 01:18:10.000
If you take it notpatiently,

1629
01:18:10.000 --> 01:18:13.170
why, your mettle is themore.

1630
01:18:13.170 --> 01:18:18.000
Adieu, trusty Pompey.

1631
01:18:18.000 --> 01:18:18.830
'Bless you, friar.

1632
01:18:18.830 --> 01:18:20.430
And you.

1633
01:18:20.430 --> 01:18:23.370
Does Bridget paint still,Pompey, ha?

1634
01:18:23.370 --> 01:18:25.270
Come your ways, sir; come.

1635
01:18:25.270 --> 01:18:28.930
You will not bail me,then, sir?

1636
01:18:28.930 --> 01:18:30.530
Then, Pompey, nor now.

1637
01:18:30.530 --> 01:18:35.730
What news abroad, friar?what news?

1638
01:18:35.730 --> 01:18:37.970
Come your ways, sir; come.

1639
01:18:37.970 --> 01:18:41.970
Go to kennel, Pompey; go.

1640
01:18:44.030 --> 01:18:46.200
What news, friar, of theduke?

1641
01:18:46.200 --> 01:18:49.570
I know none. Can you tellme of any?

1642
01:18:49.570 --> 01:18:52.070
Some say he is with theEmperor of Russia;

1643
01:18:52.070 --> 01:18:54.130
other some, he is in Rome:

1644
01:18:54.130 --> 01:18:55.730
but where is he, thinkyou?

1645
01:18:55.730 --> 01:18:57.030
I know not where; butwheresoever,

1646
01:18:57.030 --> 01:18:58.570
I wish him well.

1647
01:18:58.570 --> 01:19:00.730
It was a mad fantasticaltrick of him to steal

1648
01:19:00.730 --> 01:19:03.300
from the state, and usurpthe beggary

1649
01:19:03.300 --> 01:19:05.170
he was never born to.

1650
01:19:05.170 --> 01:19:07.730
Lord Angelo dukes it wellin his absence;

1651
01:19:07.730 --> 01:19:09.570
he puts transgression to't.

1652
01:19:09.570 --> 01:19:11.630
He does well in 't.

1653
01:19:11.630 --> 01:19:13.170
A little more lenity tolechery

1654
01:19:13.170 --> 01:19:14.630
would do no harm in him:

1655
01:19:14.630 --> 01:19:16.800
something too crabbed thatway, friar.

1656
01:19:16.800 --> 01:19:17.970
It is too general a vice,

1657
01:19:17.970 --> 01:19:19.400
and severity must cure it.

1658
01:19:19.400 --> 01:19:20.370
Yes, in good sooth,

1659
01:19:20.370 --> 01:19:22.800
the vice is of a greatkindred;

1660
01:19:22.800 --> 01:19:25.130
it is well allied:

1661
01:19:25.130 --> 01:19:26.870
but it is impossible toextirp it quite,

1662
01:19:26.870 --> 01:19:28.770
friar, till eating anddrinking be put down.

1663
01:19:28.770 --> 01:19:31.930
They say this Angelo wasnot made

1664
01:19:31.930 --> 01:19:33.230
by man and woman

1665
01:19:33.230 --> 01:19:35.370
after this downright wayof creation:

1666
01:19:35.370 --> 01:19:36.900
is it true, think you?

1667
01:19:36.900 --> 01:19:38.800
How should he be made,then?

1668
01:19:38.800 --> 01:19:41.530
Some report a sea-maidspawned him;

1669
01:19:41.530 --> 01:19:45.400
some, that he was begotbetween two stock-fishes.

1670
01:19:45.400 --> 01:19:47.770
But it is certain thatwhen he makes water

1671
01:19:47.770 --> 01:19:50.430
his urine is congealedice;

1672
01:19:50.430 --> 01:19:52.170
that I know to be true:

1673
01:19:52.170 --> 01:19:56.730
and he is a motiongenerative;

1674
01:19:56.730 --> 01:19:57.630
that's infallible.

1675
01:19:57.630 --> 01:19:59.070
You are pleasant, sir, andspeak apace.

1676
01:19:59.070 --> 01:20:01.570
Why, what a ruthless thingis this in him,

1677
01:20:01.570 --> 01:20:03.300
for the rebellion of acodpiece

1678
01:20:03.300 --> 01:20:05.370
to take away the life of aman!

1679
01:20:05.370 --> 01:20:07.830
Would the duke that isabsent have done this?

1680
01:20:07.830 --> 01:20:09.270
Ere he would have hanged aman

1681
01:20:09.270 --> 01:20:11.070
for the getting a hundredbastards,

1682
01:20:11.070 --> 01:20:14.430
he would have paid for thenursing a thousand:

1683
01:20:14.430 --> 01:20:16.170
he had some feeling of thesport:

1684
01:20:16.170 --> 01:20:17.400
he knew the service,

1685
01:20:17.400 --> 01:20:19.200
and that instructed him tomercy.

1686
01:20:19.200 --> 01:20:20.700
I never heard the absentduke

1687
01:20:20.700 --> 01:20:21.870
much detected for women;

1688
01:20:21.870 --> 01:20:23.130
he was not inclined thatway.

1689
01:20:23.130 --> 01:20:25.700
O, sir, you are deceived.

1690
01:20:25.700 --> 01:20:26.530
'Tis not possible.

1691
01:20:26.530 --> 01:20:28.270
Who, not the duke?

1692
01:20:28.270 --> 01:20:30.200
yes, your beggar of fifty;

1693
01:20:30.200 --> 01:20:33.600
and his use was to put aducat in her clack-dish:

1694
01:20:33.600 --> 01:20:37.300
the duke had crotchets inhim.

1695
01:20:37.300 --> 01:20:38.270
He would be drunk too;

1696
01:20:38.270 --> 01:20:39.970
that let me inform you.

1697
01:20:39.970 --> 01:20:41.800
You do him wrong, surely.

1698
01:20:41.800 --> 01:20:43.900
Sir, I was an inward ofhis.

1699
01:20:43.900 --> 01:20:48.870
A shy fellow was the duke:

1700
01:20:48.870 --> 01:20:52.330
and I believe I know thecause of his withdrawing.

1701
01:20:52.330 --> 01:20:55.470
What, I prithee, might bethe cause?

1702
01:20:55.470 --> 01:20:58.370
No, pardon; 'tis a secretmust be locked

1703
01:20:58.370 --> 01:21:02.000
within the teeth and thelips:

1704
01:21:02.000 --> 01:21:03.530
but this I can let youunderstand,

1705
01:21:03.530 --> 01:21:05.700
the greater file of thesubject

1706
01:21:05.700 --> 01:21:07.100
held the duke to be wise.

1707
01:21:07.100 --> 01:21:09.800
Wise! why, no question buthe was.

1708
01:21:09.800 --> 01:21:13.200
A very superficial,ignorant, unweighing fellow.

1709
01:21:14.170 --> 01:21:15.600
Either this is the envy inyou,

1710
01:21:15.600 --> 01:21:18.100
folly, or mistaking:

1711
01:21:18.100 --> 01:21:19.930
the very stream of hislife

1712
01:21:19.930 --> 01:21:21.330
and the business he hathhelmed

1713
01:21:21.330 --> 01:21:22.570
must upon a warranted need

1714
01:21:22.570 --> 01:21:24.330
give him a betterproclamation.

1715
01:21:24.330 --> 01:21:25.800
Let him be but testimonied

1716
01:21:25.800 --> 01:21:27.000
in his ownbringings-forth,

1717
01:21:27.000 --> 01:21:29.200
and he shall appear to theenvious a scholar,

1718
01:21:29.200 --> 01:21:31.770
a statesman and a soldier.

1719
01:21:31.770 --> 01:21:33.630
Therefore you speakunskilfully:

1720
01:21:33.630 --> 01:21:35.500
or if your knowledge bemore

1721
01:21:35.500 --> 01:21:36.770
it is much darkened inyour malice.

1722
01:21:36.770 --> 01:21:39.370
Sir, I know him, and Ilove him.

1723
01:21:39.370 --> 01:21:41.000
Love talks with betterknowledge,

1724
01:21:41.000 --> 01:21:42.530
and knowledge with dearerlove.

1725
01:21:42.530 --> 01:21:44.470
Come, sir, I know what Iknow.

1726
01:21:44.470 --> 01:21:45.970
I can hardly believe that,

1727
01:21:45.970 --> 01:21:47.470
since you know not whatyou speak.

1728
01:21:47.470 --> 01:21:49.870
But, if ever the dukereturn,

1729
01:21:49.870 --> 01:21:52.270
as our prayers are he may,

1730
01:21:52.270 --> 01:21:55.270
let me desire you to makeyour answer before him.

1731
01:21:55.270 --> 01:21:56.270
If it be honest you havespoke,

1732
01:21:56.270 --> 01:21:58.830
you have courage tomaintain it:

1733
01:21:58.830 --> 01:21:59.900
I am bound to call uponyou;

1734
01:21:59.900 --> 01:22:01.030
and, I pray you, yourname?

1735
01:22:01.030 --> 01:22:04.870
Sir, my name is Lucio;well known to the duke.

1736
01:22:04.870 --> 01:22:05.630
He shall know you better,sir,

1737
01:22:05.630 --> 01:22:07.300
if I live to reportyou.

1738
01:22:07.300 --> 01:22:09.730
I fear you not.

1739
01:22:09.730 --> 01:22:12.500
O, you hope the duke willreturn no more;

1740
01:22:12.500 --> 01:22:16.400
or you imagine me toounhurtful an opposite.

1741
01:22:16.400 --> 01:22:18.670
But indeed I can do youlittle harm;

1742
01:22:18.670 --> 01:22:20.670
you'll forswear thisagain.

1743
01:22:20.670 --> 01:22:23.430
I'll be hanged first:

1744
01:22:23.430 --> 01:22:26.430
thou art deceived in me,friar.

1745
01:22:26.430 --> 01:22:29.730
But no more of that.

1746
01:22:29.730 --> 01:22:32.370
Canst thou tell if Claudiodie to-morrow or no?

1747
01:22:32.370 --> 01:22:34.170
Why should he die, sir?

1748
01:22:34.170 --> 01:22:37.330
Why? For filling a bottlewith a tundish.

1749
01:22:37.330 --> 01:22:40.730
I would the duke we talkof were returned again:

1750
01:22:40.730 --> 01:22:41.900
the ungenitured agent

1751
01:22:41.900 --> 01:22:44.830
will unpeople the provincewith continency;

1752
01:22:44.830 --> 01:22:46.600
sparrows must not build inhis house-eaves,

1753
01:22:46.600 --> 01:22:49.030
because they arelecherous.

1754
01:22:49.030 --> 01:22:52.370
The duke yet would havedark deeds darkly answered;

1755
01:22:52.370 --> 01:22:54.400
he would never bring themto light:

1756
01:22:54.400 --> 01:22:57.200
would he were returned!

1757
01:22:57.200 --> 01:23:00.130
Marry, this Claudio iscondemned for untrussing.

1758
01:23:00.130 --> 01:23:07.670
Farewell, good friar: Iprithee, pray for me.

1759
01:23:07.670 --> 01:23:09.030
The duke, I say to theeagain,

1760
01:23:09.030 --> 01:23:11.130
would eat mutton onFridays.

1761
01:23:11.130 --> 01:23:13.370
He's not past it yet, andI say to thee,

1762
01:23:13.370 --> 01:23:14.870
he would mouth with abeggar,

1763
01:23:14.870 --> 01:23:16.970
though she smelt brownbread and garlic:

1764
01:23:16.970 --> 01:23:19.930
say that I said so.Farewell.

1765
01:23:23.870 --> 01:23:26.270
No might nor greatness inmortality

1766
01:23:26.270 --> 01:23:27.770
Can censure 'scape;

1767
01:23:27.770 --> 01:23:29.230
back-wounding calumny

1768
01:23:29.230 --> 01:23:31.900
The whitest virtuestrikes.

1769
01:23:31.900 --> 01:23:33.230
What king so strong

1770
01:23:33.230 --> 01:23:38.400
Can tie the gall up in theslanderous tongue?

1771
01:23:43.870 --> 01:23:47.770
Go; away with her toprison!

1772
01:23:47.770 --> 01:23:49.330
Good my lord, be merciful tome;

1773
01:23:49.330 --> 01:23:52.330
you are accounted amerciful man; good my lord.

1774
01:23:52.330 --> 01:23:54.500
Double and trebleadmonition,

1775
01:23:54.500 --> 01:23:57.300
and still forfeit in thesame kind!

1776
01:23:57.300 --> 01:23:59.270
This would make mercyswear and play the tyrant.

1777
01:23:59.270 --> 01:24:01.000
A bawd of eleven years'continuance,

1778
01:24:01.000 --> 01:24:02.170
may it please your honour.

1779
01:24:02.170 --> 01:24:03.700
My lord, this is oneLucio's

1780
01:24:03.700 --> 01:24:04.970
information against me.

1781
01:24:04.970 --> 01:24:06.600
Mistress Kate Keepdown waswith child by him

1782
01:24:06.600 --> 01:24:09.670
in the duke's time; hepromised her marriage:

1783
01:24:09.670 --> 01:24:11.170
his child is a year and aquarter old,

1784
01:24:11.170 --> 01:24:11.900
come Philip and Jacob:

1785
01:24:11.900 --> 01:24:13.030
I have kept it myself;

1786
01:24:13.030 --> 01:24:15.470
and see how he goes aboutto abuse me!

1787
01:24:15.470 --> 01:24:17.030
That fellow is a fellow ofmuch licence:

1788
01:24:17.030 --> 01:24:18.030
let him be called beforeus.

1789
01:24:18.030 --> 01:24:19.970
Away with her to prison!

1790
01:24:19.970 --> 01:24:22.900
Go to; no more words.

1791
01:24:25.270 --> 01:24:32.500
Provost, my brother Angelowill not be altered;

1792
01:24:32.500 --> 01:24:35.600
Claudio must dieto-morrow:

1793
01:24:35.600 --> 01:24:37.700
let him be furnished withdivines,

1794
01:24:37.700 --> 01:24:42.070
and have all charitablepreparation.

1795
01:24:42.070 --> 01:24:45.670
if my brother wrought bymy pity,

1796
01:24:45.670 --> 01:24:48.600
it should not be so withhim.

1797
01:24:48.600 --> 01:24:49.700
So please you,

1798
01:24:49.700 --> 01:24:51.730
this friar hath been withhim,

1799
01:24:51.730 --> 01:24:53.930
and advised him for theentertainment of death.

1800
01:24:53.930 --> 01:24:54.930
Good even, good father.

1801
01:24:54.930 --> 01:24:57.170
Bliss and goodness on you!

1802
01:24:57.170 --> 01:24:58.100
Of whence are you?

1803
01:24:58.100 --> 01:24:59.670
Not of this country,

1804
01:24:59.670 --> 01:25:00.770
though my chance is now

1805
01:25:00.770 --> 01:25:02.130
To use it for my time:

1806
01:25:02.130 --> 01:25:03.530
I am a brother of graciousorder,

1807
01:25:03.530 --> 01:25:05.530
late come from the See

1808
01:25:05.530 --> 01:25:09.270
In special business fromhis holiness.

1809
01:25:09.270 --> 01:25:11.230
What news abroad i' theworld?

1810
01:25:11.230 --> 01:25:14.730
None, but that there is sogreat

